\begin_layout Section
Results and Discussion:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
From Figure 5 and Figure 6 , the 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}$
\end_inset

coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos(\cos(x))$
\end_inset

 is nearly zero since 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos(\cos(x))$
\end_inset

 is even function and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin(nx)$
\end_inset

 is odd function.The integral over 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos(\cos(x))\sin(nx)$
\end_inset

 is zero.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos(\cos(x))$
\end_inset

 is continuous it can be constructed using lesser frequency components i.e
 k ranging from 0 to 25.But 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp(x)$
\end_inset

 is discontinuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $2m\pi$
\end_inset

 so to accomodate discontinuity high frequency components are required i.e
 k values should range more than 25.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The Riemann-Lebesgue lemma says that the Fourier coefficients converge to
 zero as |k| → ∞.The more smoother the function is ,the fast the fourier
 coefficients converges to zero.Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos(\cos(x))$
\end_inset

 is infinitely differentiable(hence smoother) its coefficients decay faster
 when compared to 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp(x)$
\end_inset

 which is discontinuous at multiples of 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi$
\end_inset

(hence not smoother).
 These rate of decay can be seen in Figures 3,4,5,6 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The integral which computes 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $b_{n}$
\end_inset

of 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp(x)$
\end_inset

 will be of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{const}{1+n^{2}}$
\end_inset

 which on loglog plot looks linear.Hence the Figure 4 is linear.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{2\pi}e^{x}\cos(nx)dx=\frac{e^{2\pi}-1}{1+n^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{2\pi}cos(cos(x))cos(kx)dx$
\end_inset

 takes the form of 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{k}$
\end_inset

 which on semilog log plot looks linear and as 
\begin_inset Formula $k\rightarrow largevalue$
\end_inset

 integral goes to zero from Riemann-Lebesgue lemma.Hence Figure 5 is linear.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The deviation of coefficients obtained from integral and leastsquares are
 
\begin_inset Formula $1.33273087034$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2.63744981915e-15$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos(\cos(x))$
\end_inset

 respectively.The values do not agree because integral approach assumes infinite
 coefficients to construct the functions whereas leastsquares tries to fit
 it to curves with 25 coefficients only(as we have taken).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos(\cos(x))$
\end_inset

 since 25 coefficients make the function closer enough the least squares
 fits properly to expected one.
 whereas for 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp(x)$
\end_inset

 because of its discontinuity it requires higher frequency coefficients,
 therefore plot from 25 coefficients approach closer to function except
 at discontinuity where disagreement is clearly seen from Figure 1.
\end_layout

